      "writtenOn": "2020-12-01T20:23:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Some of this code is a bit confusing to read because there are competing types SkSL::Expression and SkSL::dsl::Expression, SkSL::Statement vs SkSL::dsl::Statement, etc. Adding to the confusion, the dsl::Xxxxx types act like unique_ptrs that can be released-from, while the SkSL::Xxxxx types are just standard types.\n\nDo you have any preferred techniques for making this clearer? There are lots of ways to disambiguate here, since we control all the names and structures involved. I can suggest things but would rather get your take first.",
      "revId": "c31bce6e553004c1ae30060bfd36d32b2ede2d91",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2f920c27_44578389",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 32
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-02T14:45:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t think it\u0027s wise to land this without some sort of unit test.\n\nI gave this some thought and it seems like we shouldn\u0027t need anything too elaborate. What if we build DSLs, release them into SkSL, and verify that its description matches expectations? It should be easy to get good coverage this way. Example (using sorta-pseudocode for the DSL):\n\nDEF_TEST(BinaryExpressionOpPlus) {\nVar a(\"a\"), b(\"b\");\nauto x \u003d DslExpression(a + b);\nREPORTER_ASSERT(x.release()-\u003edescription() \u003d\u003d \"a + b\")\n\nauto y \u003d DslExpression(a + 1);\nREPORTER_ASSERT(y.release()-\u003edescription() \u003d\u003d \"a + 1\")\n\nauto z \u003d DslExpression(0.5 + a + (-99));\nREPORTER_ASSERT(z.release()-\u003edescription() \u003d\u003d \"0.5 + a + -99\")\n}\n\nDEF_TEST(StatementWhile) {\nauto x \u003d DslStatement(While(true), Block());\nREPORTER_ASSERT(x.release()-\u003edescription() \u003d\u003d \"while (true) {}\");\n\nauto y \u003d DslStatement(While(a !\u003d b), Block(a++));\nREPORTER_ASSERT(x.release()-\u003edescription() \u003d\u003d \"while (a !\u003d b) { a++; }\");\n}\n\netc.\n",
      "revId": "c31bce6e553004c1ae30060bfd36d32b2ede2d91",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0be43bdd_c968352c",
        "filename": "/PATCHSET_LEVEL",
        "patchSetId": 32
      },
      "lineNbr": 0,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-02T14:57:17Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027ve just thrown out a few high level ideas, that may or may not make sense. One over-arching (and related) point:\n\nWe\u0027re going to want clients to be able to use this, which means exposing the API in the include directory. Today, SkSL\u0027s headers are tightly entangled, and the new headers seem to continue that - they include quite a few other headers that really shouldn\u0027t leak out, and they include GPU headers from src/. We need to make sure there\u0027s a path to having a hermetic set of includes that declare the API, without pulling in any of our internal code (SkSL\u0027s IR, or the GPU backend).",
      "revId": "c31bce6e553004c1ae30060bfd36d32b2ede2d91",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
