      "writtenOn": "2020-12-01T21:52:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I agree. I\u0027d go further and suggest that this is one area where syntactic sugar may not be worth the compile-time headaches at all - we\u0027ve got a few other patterns for dealing with swizzles in Skia, with varying levels of safety and conciseness:\n\n- GrSwizzle is a utility struct that can describe any legal swizzle, and can be constructed from a char[4] (constexpr, so it should fail at compile time if you use an illegal swizzle string).\n- SkNx and SkVx have shuffle\u003c\u003e template methods that use variable length template argument lists (of integers) to do the operation: { skvx::shuffle\u003c0, 2, 1, 3\u003e(color) }\n\nBefore we commit to the syntactic sugar, I think we try to live without it (even just using the Swizzle() functions above.",
      "parentUuid": "8a1d41ad_024d1474",
