      "side": 1,
      "message": "I ended up running this through the preprocessor because I didn\u0027t trust what it emitted.\nAFAICS this would be equivalent and totally unambiguous:\n\n  #define TYPE(T)                                              \\\n    Expression T(Expression expr);                             \\\n    Expression T##2(Expression expr);                          \\\n    Expression T##2(Expression x, Expression y);               \\\n    Expression T##3(Expression expr);                          \\\n    Expression T##3(Expression x, Expression y);               \\\n    Expression T##3(Expression x, Expression y, Expression z); \\\n    Expression T##4(Expression expr);                          \\\n    Expression T##4(Expression x, Expression y);               \\\n    Expression T##4(Expression x, Expression y, Expression z); \\\n    Expression T##4(Expression x, Expression y, Expression z, Expression w);\n  \n  TYPE(Bool)\n  TYPE(Float)\n  TYPE(Half)\n  TYPE(Int)\n  TYPE(Short)\n  #undef TYPE\n\nUnfortunately the same pattern exists in the .cpp where it\u0027s not so easy to restructure. I want to think about this a bit. Ideally I\u0027d like to see this using templates anyway; 99% of the time, we shouldn\u0027t use macros for code generation anyway.",
